      "title": "Runner cannot satisfy the trigger scope hashes it is supposed to unblock",
      "evidence": "The triggers bind approvals to locally computed scope_hash values, but run-second-opinion.sh never computes the expected hash for the blocked tool call; it copies .scope_hash from Codex output into the artifact. The runner is invoked only as run-second-opinion.sh <review-type> <cycle-id>, so it lacks the plan path/content hash, test file path/package hash, or production tier/base binding needed to reproduce the hook's hash.",
      "recommendation": "Make the hook-created obligation explicit: persist/pass review type, cycle_id, target path, content/package/base inputs, and expected scope_hash to the runner. The runner should compute or consume that local expected hash, validate Codex output against it, and write binding.scope_hash from local data, not model output.",
      "location": "scripts/tdd/run-second-opinion.sh:211"
    },
    {
      "id": "F2",
      "severity": "P0",
      "category": "security",
      "title": "Forged review-completion entries bypass second-opinion enforcement",
      "evidence": "The plan/test/production hooks allow based only on .type, .binding.cycle_id, .binding.scope_hash, and .status == approved. They do not call validate-review-completion.sh, do not verify the audit chain, and do not require evidence that the runner produced the entry. A direct edit to .tdd/exceptions/post-red-test-edits.json with the expected hash is enough to unblock the hook.",
      "recommendation": "On every matched completion, run strict validation against the completion schema, require runner-authored audit continuity, and fail closed on missing/malformed audit data. Also protect direct writes to the completion artifact or route them through the same validator.",
